{"title_page": "Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 15em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Type of Trust\n|-\n||[[NHS hospital trust]]\n|-\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Trust Details\n|-\n|'''Last annual budget'''\n|| \u00a3822 million\n|-\n|'''Employees'''\n|| 11,000\n|-\n|'''Chair'''\n|| Sir [[Jonathan Montgomery]]<ref>[https://www.ouh.nhs.uk/about/trust-board/directors.aspx Trust Board Directors] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 29 April 2020</ref>\n|-\n|'''Chief Executive'''\n|| Dr Bruno Holthof\n|-\n\n!colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Links\n|-\n|'''Website'''\n||[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/ Oxford University Hospitals]\n|-\n|'''Care Quality Commission reports'''\n||[http://www.cqc.org.uk/directory/rth CQC]\n|-\n\n|'''Wiki-Links'''\n||[[National Health Service]]\n|-\n|}\n'''Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust''' is an English teaching hospital and part of the [[Shelford Group]]. It is one of the UK's largest teaching hospitals and one of the [[List of largest hospitals|largest hospitals]] in Europe. The Trust is made up of four hospitals \u2013 the [[John Radcliffe Hospital]] (which includes the Children's Hospital, West Wing, Eye Hospital, Heart Centre and Women's Centre), the [[Churchill Hospital]] and the [[Nuffield Orthopaedic Centre]], all located in [[Oxford]], and the [[Horton General Hospital]] in [[Banbury]], north Oxfordshire.<ref>[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/about/default.aspx About us] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 5 February 2015</ref>\n\nAs well as the four main hospitals, the trust also provides services in four [[community hospital]]s across Oxfordshire including Thame, Wallingford, Wantage and Witney. The services offered at these community hospitals are fairly basic and differ from hospital to hospital. Wantage community hospital is also accompanied by Wantage health centre whereby additional health services are provided by the trust. Other clinics and health centres serviced by the trust in Oxfordshire includes Bicester and Oxford with the trust also providing some services in clinics and hospitals in neighbouring counties.<ref>[http://www.nhs.uk/Services/Trusts/HospitalsAndClinics/DefaultView.aspx?id=1031 Hospitals and clinics] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 1 January 2016</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Trust was formed in 2011 by a merger with the Nuffield Orthopaedic Centre NHS Trust.  It achieved [[Foundation Trust]] status in October 2015.<ref>[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/news/article.aspx?id=364 Oxford University Hospitals becomes a Foundation Trust] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 17 October 2015</ref>  Sir [[Jonathan Michael]], then chief executive, announced in November 2014 that he planned to retire in 2015 \u2013 by which time it was hoped that the Trust would achieve [[Foundation Trust]] status.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oxfordshire's major hospitals will conduct international search for new chief executive|url=http://www.heraldseries.co.uk/news/11597755.Oxfordshire_s_major_hospitals_will_conduct_international_search_for_new_chief_executive/|accessdate=2 December 2014|publisher=The Herald|date=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Trust is to set up an independent business subsidiary in London in partnership with the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Mayo Clinic]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayo Clinic, Oxford to collaborate on research and innovation|url=http://www.healthcareitnews.com/news/mayo-clinic-oxford-collaborate-research-and-innovation|accessdate=23 December 2017|publisher=Healthcare IT news|date=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe trust has one of the 11 Genomics Medicines Centres associated with [[Genomics England]] which will open across England in February 2014. All the data produced in the 100,000 Genomes project will be made available to drugs companies and researchers to help them create precision drugs for future generations.<ref>{{cite news|title=NHS DNA scheme to fight cancer and genetic diseases|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-30558112|accessdate=22 December 2014|work=BBC News|date=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPart of the Trust's former [[Littlemore Hospital]] site is to be developed for housing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Residents' appeal pays off as unmarked graves are saved|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/yourtown/wallingford/11821662.Residents____appeal_pays_off_as_unmarked_graves_are_saved/|accessdate=11 March 2015|publisher=Oxford times|date=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt is one of the biggest provider of specialised services in England, which generated an income of \u00a3356 million in 2014/5.<ref>{{cite news|title=Analysed: The biggest NHS providers of specialised services|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/home/analysed-the-biggest-nhs-providers-of-specialised-services/5091147.article|accessdate=16 November 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 NHS England planned to remove the contract for [[PET-CT]] scanning from the Trust\u2019s Churchill Hospital and award it to a private contractor, [[InHealth Group|InHealth]]. This was opposed by local MPs, and 10,000 people signed a petition against the move, saying it could produce an inferior service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/13/halt-privatisation-of-cancer-screening-or-risk-patient-harm-mps-tell-nhs-england|title=Halt privatisation of cancer scanning or risk patient harm, MPs tell NHS England|last=|first=|date=13 March 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Through its solicitors the NHS then threatened to sue the Trust if it sided with opponents of the plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/apr/03/oxford-hospital-trust-faced-nhs-defamation-threat|title=Oxford hospital trust faced defamation threat from NHS|last=|first=|date=3 April 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The Trust then intended to appeal against the decision but backed down after a phone call from NHS England's chairman. NHS England subsequently changed its mind, and agreed that the scanners would stay in the hospital, but InHealth was given the contract to provide the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/oxford-university-hospitals-nhs-foundation-trust/u-turn-on-plans-to-strip-trust-of-cancer-scanning-service/7025914.article|title=U-turn on plans to strip trust of cancer scanning service|last=|first=|date=12 September 2019|website=Health Services Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n==Performance==\n[[File:Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust A&E performance 2005-18.png|thumb|Four-hour target in the emergency department quarterly figures from [[NHS England]] Data from https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/]]\n\nIn September 2016, the trust was selected by [[NHS England]] as one of twelve [[Global Digital Exemplar]]s.<ref>{{cite news|title=New plans to expand the use of digital technology across the NHS|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-plans-to-expand-the-use-of-digital-technology-across-the-nhs|accessdate=9 September 2016|work=gov.uk|publisher=Department of Health and The Rt Hon Jeremy Hunt MP|ref=GDE}}</ref>\n\nThe trust halved the number patients medically fit for discharge but stuck in acute beds between January and June 2016 by employing 60 social care workers to provide support in patients' homes after discharge.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Oxford Hospitals chief reveals delayed transfers turnaround|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/topics/quality-and-performance/new-oxford-hospitals-chief-reveals-delayed-transfers-turnaround/7006113.article|accessdate=3 October 2016|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the [[Care Quality Commission]] downgraded the trust's rating from \u201cgood\u201d to \u201crequires improvement\u201d because  \u201cAcross [[John Radcliffe Hospital]]\u2019s wards and in the main theatres the state and repair of the walls, floors, doors and work surfaces were such that adequate cleaning could not always be assured.\u201d  There were other problems affecting infection control in the operating theatres.<ref>{{cite news |title=Major teaching trust told to make urgent infection risk improvements |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/oxford-university-hospitals-nhs-trust/major-teaching-trust-told-to-make-urgent-infection-risk-improvements/7025249.article |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Staffing==\nIn September 2018 the chief executive, Bruno Holthof, reported that the trust had about 450 nursing vacancies, because of the effect of Brexit and the high cost of living in the area, and had to close beds as a result.  There were 3,210 nurses and health visitors employed in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=BREXIT: Exodus of EU nurses leaves Oxford hospitals with 'severe staff shortage' |url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/16909533.brexit-exodus-of-eu-nurses-leaves-oxford-hospitals-with-severe-staff-shortage/?ref=twtrec |accessdate=1 October 2018 |newspaper=Oxford Mail |date=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Oxford Health NHS Foundation Trust]]\n* [[List of NHS trusts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/ Oxford University Hospitals NHS Trust Website]\n\n[[Category:Health in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:NHS foundation trusts]]\n[[Category:Shelford Group]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 15em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Type of Trust\n|-\n||[[NHS hospital trust]]\n|-\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Trust Details\n|-\n|'''Last annual budget'''\n|| \u00a3822 million\n|-\n|'''Employees'''\n|| 11,000\n|-\n|'''Chair'''\n|| Dame [[Fiona Caldicott]]\n|-\n|'''Chief Executive'''\n|| Dr [[Bruno Holthof]]\n|-\n\n!colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#efefef\" | Links\n|-\n|'''Website'''\n||[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/ Oxford University Hospitals]\n|-\n|'''Care Quality Commission reports'''\n||[http://www.cqc.org.uk/directory/rth CQC]\n|-\n\n|'''Wiki-Links'''\n||[[National Health Service]]\n|-\n|}\n'''Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust''' is an English teaching hospital and part of the [[Shelford Group]]. It is one of the UK's largest teaching hospitals and one of the [[List of largest hospitals|largest hospitals]] in Europe. The Trust is made up of four hospitals \u2013 the [[John Radcliffe Hospital]] (which includes the Children's Hospital, West Wing, Eye Hospital, Heart Centre and Women's Centre), the [[Churchill Hospital]] and the [[Nuffield Orthopaedic Centre]], all located in [[Oxford]], and the [[Horton General Hospital]] in [[Banbury]], north Oxfordshire.<ref>[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/about/default.aspx About us] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 5 February 2015</ref>\n\nAs well as the four main hospitals, the trust also provides services in four [[community hospital]]s across Oxfordshire including Thame, Wallingford, Wantage and Witney. The services offered at these community hospitals are fairly basic and differ from hospital to hospital. Wantage community hospital is also accompanied by Wantage health centre whereby additional health services are provided by the trust. Other clinics and health centres serviced by the trust in Oxfordshire includes Bicester and Oxford with the trust also providing some services in clinics and hospitals in neighbouring counties.<ref>[http://www.nhs.uk/Services/Trusts/HospitalsAndClinics/DefaultView.aspx?id=1031 Hospitals and clinics] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 1 January 2016</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Trust was formed in 2011 by a merger with the Nuffield Orthopaedic Centre NHS Trust.  It achieved [[Foundation Trust]] status in October 2015.<ref>[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/news/article.aspx?id=364 Oxford University Hospitals becomes a Foundation Trust] Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Retrieved 17 October 2015</ref>  Sir [[Jonathan Michael]], then chief executive, announced in November 2014 that he planned to retire in 2015 \u2013 by which time it was hoped that the Trust would achieve [[Foundation Trust]] status.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oxfordshire's major hospitals will conduct international search for new chief executive|url=http://www.heraldseries.co.uk/news/11597755.Oxfordshire_s_major_hospitals_will_conduct_international_search_for_new_chief_executive/|accessdate=2 December 2014|publisher=The Herald|date=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Trust is to set up an independent business subsidiary in London in partnership with the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Mayo Clinic]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayo Clinic, Oxford to collaborate on research and innovation|url=http://www.healthcareitnews.com/news/mayo-clinic-oxford-collaborate-research-and-innovation|accessdate=23 December 2017|publisher=Healthcare IT news|date=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe trust has one of the 11 Genomics Medicines Centres associated with [[Genomics England]] which will open across England in February 2014. All the data produced in the 100,000 Genomes project will be made available to drugs companies and researchers to help them create precision drugs for future generations.<ref>{{cite news|title=NHS DNA scheme to fight cancer and genetic diseases|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-30558112|accessdate=22 December 2014|work=BBC News|date=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPart of the Trust's former [[Littlemore Hospital]] site is to be developed for housing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Residents' appeal pays off as unmarked graves are saved|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/yourtown/wallingford/11821662.Residents____appeal_pays_off_as_unmarked_graves_are_saved/|accessdate=11 March 2015|publisher=Oxford times|date=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt is one of the biggest provider of specialised services in England, which generated an income of \u00a3356 million in 2014/5.<ref>{{cite news|title=Analysed: The biggest NHS providers of specialised services|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/home/analysed-the-biggest-nhs-providers-of-specialised-services/5091147.article|accessdate=16 November 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 NHS England planned to remove the contract for [[PET-CT]] scanning from the Trust\u2019s Churchill Hospital and award it to a private contractor, [[InHealth Group|InHealth]]. This was opposed by local MPs, and 10,000 people signed a petition against the move, saying it could produce an inferior service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/13/halt-privatisation-of-cancer-screening-or-risk-patient-harm-mps-tell-nhs-england|title=Halt privatisation of cancer scanning or risk patient harm, MPs tell NHS England|last=|first=|date=13 March 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Through its solicitors the NHS then threatened to sue the Trust if it sided with opponents of the plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/apr/03/oxford-hospital-trust-faced-nhs-defamation-threat|title=Oxford hospital trust faced defamation threat from NHS|last=|first=|date=3 April 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The Trust then intended to appeal against the decision but backed down after a phone call from NHS England's chairman. NHS England subsequently changed its mind, and agreed that the scanners would stay in the hospital, but InHealth was given the contract to provide the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/oxford-university-hospitals-nhs-foundation-trust/u-turn-on-plans-to-strip-trust-of-cancer-scanning-service/7025914.article|title=U-turn on plans to strip trust of cancer scanning service|last=|first=|date=12 September 2019|website=Health Services Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n==Performance==\n[[File:Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust A&E performance 2005-18.png|thumb|Four-hour target in the emergency department quarterly figures from [[NHS England]] Data from https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/]]\n\nIn September 2016, the trust was selected by [[NHS England]] as one of twelve [[Global Digital Exemplar]]s.<ref>{{cite news|title=New plans to expand the use of digital technology across the NHS|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-plans-to-expand-the-use-of-digital-technology-across-the-nhs|accessdate=9 September 2016|work=gov.uk|publisher=Department of Health and The Rt Hon Jeremy Hunt MP|ref=GDE}}</ref>\n\nThe trust halved the number patients medically fit for discharge but stuck in acute beds between January and June 2016 by employing 60 social care workers to provide support in patients' homes after discharge.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Oxford Hospitals chief reveals delayed transfers turnaround|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/topics/quality-and-performance/new-oxford-hospitals-chief-reveals-delayed-transfers-turnaround/7006113.article|accessdate=3 October 2016|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the [[Care Quality Commission]] downgraded the trust's rating from \u201cgood\u201d to \u201crequires improvement\u201d because  \u201cAcross [[John Radcliffe Hospital]]\u2019s wards and in the main theatres the state and repair of the walls, floors, doors and work surfaces were such that adequate cleaning could not always be assured.\u201d  There were other problems affecting infection control in the operating theatres.<ref>{{cite news |title=Major teaching trust told to make urgent infection risk improvements |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/oxford-university-hospitals-nhs-trust/major-teaching-trust-told-to-make-urgent-infection-risk-improvements/7025249.article |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Staffing==\nIn September 2018 the chief executive, Bruno Holthof, reported that the trust had about 450 nursing vacancies, because of the effect of Brexit and the high cost of living in the area, and had to close beds as a result.  There were 3,210 nurses and health visitors employed in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=BREXIT: Exodus of EU nurses leaves Oxford hospitals with 'severe staff shortage' |url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/16909533.brexit-exodus-of-eu-nurses-leaves-oxford-hospitals-with-severe-staff-shortage/?ref=twtrec |accessdate=1 October 2018 |newspaper=Oxford Mail |date=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Oxford Health NHS Foundation Trust]]\n* [[List of NHS trusts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ouh.nhs.uk/ Oxford University Hospitals NHS Trust Website]\n\n[[Category:Health in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:NHS foundation trusts]]\n[[Category:Shelford Group]]\n", "name_user": "Illuminate2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sir Jonathan Montgomery succeed Dame Fiona Caldicott as the Chair of the Oxford University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust on the 1st April 2019 - https://www.ouh.nhs.uk/about/trust-board/directors.aspx", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_University_Hospitals_NHS_Foundation_Trust"}
